- He's good, isn't he?
- Fantastic.

282
00:14:51,162 --> 00:14:53,596
l'm off, then.
See you next week.

283
00:14:53,682 --> 00:14:54,592
Let's go.

284
00:14:55,682 --> 00:14:56,637
Come on.

285
00:15:06,762 --> 00:15:08,673
Why do we have to leave?

286
00:15:08,762 --> 00:15:10,161
Beat the traffic.

287
00:15:10,242 --> 00:15:12,153
Long walk back to the car,

288
00:15:12,242 --> 00:15:13,960
we'll be stuck for hours.

289
00:15:14,042 --> 00:15:15,760
But they might score again.

290
00:15:15,842 --> 00:15:17,753
There's a remote possibility.

291
00:15:17,842 --> 00:15:19,753
But it won't be this afternoon.

292
00:15:19,842 --> 00:15:21,753
Joke. lf you're an Arsenal fan,

293
00:15:21,842 --> 00:15:23,753
you get used to jokes like that.

294
00:15:23,842 --> 00:15:24,797
l will.

295
00:15:26,042 --> 00:15:27,953
Who d'you think played best?

296
00:15:28,042 --> 00:15:29,953
Dunno. But Sammels was rubbish.

297
00:15:30,042 --> 00:15:31,441
l don't think so.

298
00:15:31,522 --> 00:15:32,921
Crowd didn't understand

299
00:15:33,002 --> 00:15:34,720
what he was trying to do.

300
00:15:34,802 --> 00:15:36,235
They were on to him

301
00:15:36,322 --> 00:15:38,233
before he'd done anything wrong.

302
00:15:38,322 --> 00:15:40,233
- l disagree.
- Oh, you do?

303
00:15:40,322 --> 00:15:43,234
One afternoon at football,
you're Kenneth Wolstenholme.

304
00:15:43,322 --> 00:15:46,234
Who did YOU think
played the best?

305
00:15:46,322 --> 00:15:48,233
[Music drowns out dialogue]

306
00:16:07,762 --> 00:16:09,673
Might make an Arsenal defence

307
00:16:09,762 --> 00:16:11,161
of them yet, Robert.

308
00:16:11,242 --> 00:16:12,152
Yes, sir.

309
00:16:13,442 --> 00:16:16,161
Em, sir, you going
to Highbury next week?

310
00:16:16,242 --> 00:16:17,561
- Nah.
- Oh.

311
00:16:17,642 --> 00:16:19,041
'Course l'm going.

312
00:16:19,122 --> 00:16:21,556
Want me to get you
a programme?

313
00:16:21,642 --> 00:16:23,041
lt's cash in advance.

314
00:16:23,122 --> 00:16:25,033
l've been caught too many times.

315
00:16:25,122 --> 00:16:26,521
No, it's not that.

316
00:16:26,602 --> 00:16:27,512
Em...

317
00:16:27,602 --> 00:16:29,035
could l come with you?

318
00:16:30,762 --> 00:16:32,593
That'd be a bit difficult.

319
00:16:33,762 --> 00:16:36,196
To be honest,
between you and me,

320
00:16:36,282 --> 00:16:39,194
- l go to the pub first.
- l could wait outside.

321
00:16:39,282 --> 00:16:42,194
l stand on the North Bank.
You wouldn't see.

322
00:16:42,282 --> 00:16:45,194
- l'd go down the front.
- Your mum'd love that.

323
00:16:45,282 --> 00:16:46,715
She says l have to go

324
00:16:46,802 --> 00:16:48,235
with a responsible adult.

325
00:16:48,322 --> 00:16:50,756
Saturday's the one
day of the week

326
00:16:50,842 --> 00:16:52,753
when l'm NOT
a responsible adult.

327
00:16:52,842 --> 00:16:54,753
l turn into someone your age.

328
00:16:54,842 --> 00:16:56,275
Not as sensible.

329
00:16:56,362 --> 00:16:58,080
She won't have to find out.

330
00:16:58,162 --> 00:17:00,073
l'm sorry, Robert, l can't.

331
00:17:01,162 --> 00:17:02,561
Well, not this week.

332
00:17:02,642 --> 00:17:04,553
Maybe some other time, eh?

333
00:17:04,642 --> 00:17:07,076
Next season when
you've grown a bit?

334
00:17:07,162 --> 00:17:08,561
Get you a programme.

335
00:17:08,642 --> 00:17:11,554
Cash in advance unnecessary,
on this occasion.

336
00:17:11,642 --> 00:17:13,041
To hell with it,

337
00:17:13,122 --> 00:17:14,840
you can have one for free.

338
00:17:14,922 --> 00:17:15,832
Thanks, sir.

339
00:17:19,802 --> 00:17:20,917
Bollocks!

340
00:17:21,002 --> 00:17:22,117
BOLLOCKS!

341
00:17:24,362 --> 00:17:26,318
[Paul] Nothing to worry about.

342
00:17:26,402 --> 00:17:29,314
His handwriting's a disgrace
to the human race

343
00:17:29,402 --> 00:17:32,314
but he's very bright
and enjoys the lessons.

344
00:17:32,402 --> 00:17:35,314
He does. He's always
goin' on about you.

345
00:17:35,402 --> 00:17:38,314
lt's my enthusiasm for
Steinbeck's prose style.

346
00:17:38,402 --> 00:17:40,313
Either that or something else.

347
00:17:40,402 --> 00:17:41,596
The football, you mean?

348
00:17:41,682 --> 00:17:44,594
Robert thinks they might
win the championship

349
00:17:44,682 --> 00:17:46,559
for the first time since 1 970.

350
00:17:47,642 --> 00:17:48,757
1 971 .

351
00:17:48,842 --> 00:17:50,480
Gotta get things
like that right.

352
00:17:50,562 --> 00:17:51,472
Absolutely.

353
00:17:51,562 --> 00:17:53,393
Did he tell you what happened

354
00:17:53,482 --> 00:17:54,915
after football training?

355
00:17:55,002 --> 00:17:57,914
He asked me if l'd take him
to the Arsenal.

356
00:17:58,002 --> 00:17:59,435
Mr Ashworth, l'm so sorry.

357
00:17:59,522 --> 00:18:01,911
He just seemed uptight about it.

358
00:18:02,002 --> 00:18:04,516
His dad and me are
recently separated.

359
00:18:04,602 --> 00:18:06,911
lt was his dad
he used to go with.

360
00:18:07,002 --> 00:18:10,312
- You don't wanna take him?
- Don't know anything about it.

361
00:18:10,402 --> 00:18:12,313
l very much doubt if he'd care.

362
00:18:12,402 --> 00:18:15,075
l can tell you everything
you need to know

363
00:18:15,162 --> 00:18:16,595
in about five minutes.

364
00:18:16,682 --> 00:18:19,071
She seemed to enjoy
the Elizabethans

365
00:18:19,162 --> 00:18:20,595
but when we moved on,

366
00:18:20,682 --> 00:18:23,242
she slipped back.
She dropped four places.

367
00:18:23,322 --> 00:18:25,233
Was it four? No, six.

368
00:18:25,322 --> 00:18:27,711
Which l found
a little disappointing

369
00:18:27,802 --> 00:18:30,714
though l'm not sure
that she did.

370
00:18:30,802 --> 00:18:32,440
No. She's got her heart set

371
00:18:32,522 --> 00:18:35,434
on a hairdresser's
apprenticeship.

372
00:18:36,562 --> 00:18:37,472
Right.

373
00:18:40,562 --> 00:18:41,961
Thanks very much, then.

374
00:18:47,002 --> 00:18:49,311
[Paul]
You come out the tube station,

375
00:18:49,402 --> 00:18:52,314
cross over the street
and in that entrance there,

376
00:18:52,402 --> 00:18:54,199
you buy unreserved seats, £7.

377
00:18:54,282 --> 00:18:55,715
My ex can pay.

378
00:18:55,802 --> 00:18:57,713
- He's a Spurs fan, isn't he?
- Yeah.

379
00:18:57,802 --> 00:18:59,235
l'd go for £1 2 seats.

380
00:18:59,322 --> 00:19:01,711
Sting the bastard
for all you can get.

381
00:19:01,802 --> 00:19:03,201
Thank you so much.

382
00:19:03,282 --> 00:19:04,681
You've been really helpful.

383
00:19:06,642 --> 00:19:08,553
Hello, Mr Johnson.
How are you?

384
00:19:08,642 --> 00:19:10,553
Evening. Suppose you're feeling

385
00:19:10,642 --> 00:19:12,075
pretty pleased with life.

386
00:19:12,162 --> 00:19:12,442
[Music on radio]

387
00:19:12,442 --> 00:19:13,670
[Music on radio]

388
00:19:13,762 --> 00:19:16,595
# Are you ready to be...
heartbroken?

389
00:19:16,682 --> 00:19:18,240
Oh, fuck it!

390
00:19:18,322 --> 00:19:22,679
# Well, you better
get ready now, baby

391
00:19:22,762 --> 00:19:24,480
Would you like a lift?

392
00:19:24,562 --> 00:19:25,995
# Get ready to bleed

393
00:19:26,082 --> 00:19:27,800
You don't know where l live.

394
00:19:27,882 --> 00:19:29,315
Yes, l do. Crouch End.

395
00:19:29,402 --> 00:19:30,960
lt's on my way home.

396
00:19:31,042 --> 00:19:33,476
[Radio presenter]
'Don't forget, l'll be back

397
00:19:33,562 --> 00:19:35,917
'with all the top
sports stories...

398
00:19:36,002 --> 00:19:37,435
'But first of all...'

399
00:19:37,522 --> 00:19:38,875
How about you?

400
00:19:38,962 --> 00:19:39,951
Arsenal.

401
00:19:40,042 --> 00:19:42,431
lnside the stadium
or just nearby?

402
00:19:47,442 --> 00:19:48,841
[Radio presenter] 'Number one,

403
00:19:48,922 --> 00:19:50,833
'Abigail's Party,

404
00:19:50,922 --> 00:19:53,834
You really are Mr Popular,
aren't you?

405
00:19:53,922 --> 00:19:55,833
All those queues at your desk.

406
00:19:55,922 --> 00:19:57,275
'..Live commentary

407
00:19:57,362 --> 00:19:59,273
'on three races
from that meeting.'

408
00:19:59,362 --> 00:20:00,511
Sorry.

409
00:20:00,602 --> 00:20:02,320
'And the main one at 3.45.

410
00:20:02,402 --> 00:20:04,313
'Now the main sports stories.'

411
00:20:04,402 --> 00:20:07,792
What were you talking to
Robert Parker's mother about?

412
00:20:07,882 --> 00:20:09,793
'..Suspended Arsenal's
Paul Davis...'

413
00:20:09,882 --> 00:20:11,281
Shit! Fuck! Bollocks!

414
00:20:11,362 --> 00:20:12,477
l'm sorry?

415
00:20:13,562 --> 00:20:14,517
Paul Davis.

416
00:20:15,562 --> 00:20:16,961
Who's Paul Davis?

417
00:20:17,042 --> 00:20:17,952
Arsenal.

418
00:20:18,042 --> 00:20:19,475
Were we talking about him?

419
00:20:19,562 --> 00:20:21,473
'..Signed a four-year
contract...'

420
00:20:21,562 --> 00:20:22,961
Sorry. l wasn't listening.

421
00:20:23,042 --> 00:20:24,953
'..Olympic headlines
from Seoul,

422
00:20:25,042 --> 00:20:27,351
'Linford Christie's
given the all-clear...'

423
00:20:27,442 --> 00:20:28,875
- Arsenal.
- Yes, you said.

424
00:20:28,962 --> 00:20:31,874
No, l was talking
to Robert Parker's mother

425
00:20:31,962 --> 00:20:32,917
about Arsenal.

426
00:20:33,002 --> 00:20:33,957
God!

427
00:20:35,002 --> 00:20:36,435
l'm in the wrong job.

428
00:20:36,522 --> 00:20:38,240
Well, l'm in the wrong life.

429
00:20:38,322 --> 00:20:41,234
l spent hours preparing
for a parents' evening.

430
00:20:41,322 --> 00:20:44,234
No one could think
of two words to say to me.

431
00:20:44,322 --> 00:20:45,755
Yet they queue for hours

432
00:20:45,842 --> 00:20:47,560
to hear your pearls of wisdom

433
00:20:47,642 --> 00:20:50,554
on next week's game
against Wolves United!

434
00:20:50,642 --> 00:20:51,552
Yeah...

435
00:20:52,962 --> 00:20:54,680
Just Wolves. No United.

436
00:20:54,762 --> 00:20:56,195
Look, l'm sorry.

437
00:20:56,282 --> 00:20:57,681
lt must seem unfair.

438
00:20:57,762 --> 00:20:59,161
Yes, it does, actually.

439
00:21:00,762 --> 00:21:02,161
lt's the next left.

440
00:21:06,762 --> 00:21:09,196
Maybe you're too
uptight with them.

441
00:21:09,282 --> 00:21:10,681
Maybe you should just...

442
00:21:10,762 --> 00:21:12,195
be yourself more.

443
00:21:12,282 --> 00:21:15,672
All those files and folders
and what have you.

444
00:21:15,762 --> 00:21:17,480
That lS me being myself.

445
00:21:22,562 --> 00:21:23,961
lt's just here.

446
00:21:36,402 --> 00:21:38,313
D'you want a cup of coffee?

447
00:21:38,402 --> 00:21:39,596
OK.

448
00:21:39,682 --> 00:21:41,081
You don't have to.

449
00:21:41,162 --> 00:21:44,074
No, no, no. l'd...
Yeah, l'd like to.

450
00:21:50,162 --> 00:21:51,754
What are these for, then?

451
00:21:53,162 --> 00:21:56,074
They're not for anything.
They just look nice.

452
00:21:56,162 --> 00:21:57,595
Are they yours?

453
00:21:57,682 --> 00:21:58,592
No.

454
00:21:59,682 --> 00:22:01,081
Jo's. My flat-mate.

455
00:22:02,162 --> 00:22:03,561
lt's her place.

456
00:22:03,642 --> 00:22:05,553
She's away at the moment.

457
00:22:08,762 --> 00:22:10,161
Can l smoke?

458
00:22:13,762 --> 00:22:14,717
No.

459
00:22:21,162 --> 00:22:23,073
You can stay the night, though,

460
00:22:23,162 --> 00:22:24,561
if you want.

461
00:23:28,562 --> 00:23:29,961
Not on the carpet.

462
00:23:30,042 --> 00:23:31,441
l can't afford it.

463
00:23:45,762 --> 00:23:48,674
You might have
the decency to run.

464
00:23:48,762 --> 00:23:51,674
Then we wouldn't
be doing it together.

465
00:23:51,762 --> 00:23:52,672
Cocky cow.

466
00:23:52,762 --> 00:23:54,673
lt's just a fact. Look.

467
00:23:55,762 --> 00:23:56,877
OK! OK!

468
00:23:56,962 --> 00:23:58,361
l HATE you!

469
00:24:06,562 --> 00:24:08,473
l owe you a new carpet.

470
00:24:08,562 --> 00:24:10,473
Well, maybe a new spare bed.

471
00:24:10,562 --> 00:24:12,473
You shagged
the football hooligan!

472
00:24:12,562 --> 00:24:13,961
l knew it! l knew it!

473
00:24:14,042 --> 00:24:15,760
He's not a football hooligan.

474
00:24:15,842 --> 00:24:17,560
So he HAS read Byron?

475
00:24:17,642 --> 00:24:19,394
He's bound to have done!

476
00:24:20,642 --> 00:24:23,554
lt doesn't really matter
if he hasn't.

477
00:24:23,642 --> 00:24:25,360
Who'd have thought it, eh?

478
00:24:25,442 --> 00:24:28,354
''lron Knickers'' Hughes
ending up with a yob.

479
00:24:28,442 --> 00:24:29,841
He's not a yob

480
00:24:29,922 --> 00:24:32,038
and l'm not ending up with him.

481
00:24:32,122 --> 00:24:33,555
You wanna bet?

482
00:24:35,962 --> 00:24:37,395
Where are you off to?

483
00:24:37,482 --> 00:24:38,551
l'm starving.

484
00:24:38,642 --> 00:24:41,395
l was thinking of ringing
for a pizza.

485
00:24:42,602 --> 00:24:44,399
Have you read Byron?

486
00:24:44,482 --> 00:24:45,517
What?

487
00:24:45,602 --> 00:24:48,878
Have you read
any of Byron's poems?

488
00:24:48,962 --> 00:24:49,872
Yeah.

489
00:24:51,322 --> 00:24:54,678
''The Assyrian came down
like a wolf on the fold

490
00:24:54,762 --> 00:24:56,673
''and his somethings
were gleaming

491
00:24:56,762 --> 00:24:58,673
''in black and old gold.'' Crap.

492
00:24:58,762 --> 00:25:00,195
What are those?

493
00:25:01,402 --> 00:25:03,120
My...Arsenal boxer shorts.

494
00:25:03,202 --> 00:25:04,920
They're not my best ones.

495
00:25:05,002 --> 00:25:06,401
l was running out.

496
00:25:06,482 --> 00:25:08,393
But you're willing to show them

497
00:25:08,482 --> 00:25:10,040
to another human being.

498
00:25:10,122 --> 00:25:12,431
l wasn't exactly
showing them to you.

499
00:25:12,522 --> 00:25:14,956
What d'you wanna know
about Byron for?

500
00:25:15,042 --> 00:25:17,954
Um...a bet.

501
00:25:18,042 --> 00:25:19,475
Did you win?

502
00:25:19,562 --> 00:25:20,995
l don't think so.

503
00:25:27,922 --> 00:25:29,355
Stay in line!

504
00:25:29,442 --> 00:25:31,831
Right, now push up!
Out! Out!

505
00:25:31,922 --> 00:25:33,321
That's it! Good lads.

506
00:25:33,402 --> 00:25:34,517
Offside, referee!

507
00:25:35,602 --> 00:25:36,512
Offside!

508
00:25:36,602 --> 00:25:37,557
Ref!

509
00:25:38,842 --> 00:25:40,753
Oi, ref, he was miles off.

510
00:25:40,842 --> 00:25:42,241
lt's not M Y fault.

511
00:25:42,322 --> 00:25:44,233
Too good a coach for this level.

512
00:25:44,322 --> 00:25:45,755
What's the score?

513
00:25:45,842 --> 00:25:46,797
One-all.

514
00:25:48,162 --> 00:25:51,552
lf you count that POXY GOAL
they just scored.

515
00:25:51,642 --> 00:25:53,075
What's this, Cup or League?

516
00:25:53,162 --> 00:25:54,561
Cup, quarter-final.

517
00:25:54,642 --> 00:25:56,155
- How long left?
- Fifteen.

518
00:25:57,442 --> 00:26:00,354
l wanted to talk to you
about a vacancy.

519
00:26:00,442 --> 00:26:02,876
Rosie Hunter's
handed in her notice.

520
00:26:02,962 --> 00:26:05,874
l wondered whether you'd be
interested in applying.

521
00:26:05,962 --> 00:26:07,361
Head of Year?

522
00:26:07,442 --> 00:26:08,557
Um...well...

523
00:26:08,642 --> 00:26:11,076
Obviously not the most
attractive offer

524
00:26:11,162 --> 00:26:12,595
you've ever had.

525
00:26:12,682 --> 00:26:14,593
Come on, Ben! Get back with him!

526
00:26:14,682 --> 00:26:15,717
Sorry, Ted.

527
00:26:15,802 --> 00:26:18,191
l haven't fired you
with enthusiasm.

528
00:26:18,282 --> 00:26:19,681
lt's a lot of work.

529
00:26:19,762 --> 00:26:21,673
What do l wanna
do more work for?

530
00:26:21,762 --> 00:26:22,717
More money?

531
00:26:22,802 --> 00:26:24,713
l've got enough to pay my rent,

532
00:26:24,802 --> 00:26:26,201
enough for my season ticket

533
00:26:26,282 --> 00:26:28,193
and a couple of records a month.

534
00:26:28,282 --> 00:26:29,681
Got no family.

535
00:26:29,762 --> 00:26:31,673
l'd like you to think about it.

536
00:26:31,762 --> 00:26:33,957
Sorry. There's nothing
to think about.

537
00:26:34,042 --> 00:26:35,953
Come on, Sam! Put it away!

538
00:26:38,082 --> 00:26:38,992
YES!

539
00:26:46,442 --> 00:26:47,875
[Paul] Why aren't adults

540
00:26:47,962 --> 00:26:50,396
supposed to go mad
about anything?

541
00:26:50,482 --> 00:26:52,393
You've got to keep a lid on it.

542
00:26:52,482 --> 00:26:53,881
And if you don't,

543
00:26:53,962 --> 00:26:55,873
then people
are apparently entitled

544
00:26:55,962 --> 00:26:57,680
to say what they like.

545
00:26:57,762 --> 00:27:00,196
You haven't grown up,
you're a moron.

546
00:27:00,282 --> 00:27:02,671
Your conversation
is trivial and boorish.

547
00:27:02,762 --> 00:27:05,196
You can't express
your emotional needs.

548
00:27:05,282 --> 00:27:07,193
You can't relate
to your children

549
00:27:07,282 --> 00:27:09,477
and you die -
lonely and miserable.

550
00:27:09,562 --> 00:27:11,280
But you know, what the hell?

551
00:27:11,362 --> 00:27:13,273
Every cloud has a silver lining.

552
00:27:13,442 --> 00:27:16,195
Not on your own.
How many more times?

553
00:27:16,282 --> 00:27:19,194
